PL/SQL Programming

Introduction to PL/SQL
PL/SQL (Procedural Language/SQL) is Oracle's procedural extension of SQL.
It combines SQL statements with programming constructs to build database applications.
Features of PL/SQL
Supports variables and constants.
Provides conditional statements and loops.
Includes exception handling for error management.
Improves performance by reducing database-server communication.
PL/SQL Block Structure

A PL/SQL block consists of:

Declaration Section
Execution Section
Exception Handling Section
Variables and Data Types
Variables are used to store data values.
Common data types include NUMBER, VARCHAR2, DATE, and BOOLEAN.
Control Structures
IF-ELSE statements for decision making.
CASE statements for multiple conditions.
Loops such as FOR LOOP, WHILE LOOP, and LOOP.
Exception Handling
Used to handle runtime errors gracefully.
Helps improve application reliability and maintainability.
Cursors
Cursors are used to retrieve multiple rows from a query result.
Types:
Implicit Cursor
Explicit Cursor
Stored Procedures and Functions
Procedures perform a specific task and may not return a value.
Functions return a value after execution.
Both improve code reusability and maintainability.